<paragraph id="8BBDFC7E7B6ED21FFF6FFEB5FE7FFED7" blockId="10.[151,1436,294,678]" box="[151,438,294,320]" pageId="10" pageNumber="11">
<heading id="D0F54B127B6ED21FFF6FFEB5FE7FFED7" bold="true" box="[151,438,294,320]" fontSize="11" level="1" pageId="10" pageNumber="11" reason="1">
<taxonomicName id="4C0287FD7B6ED21FFF6FFEB5FE7FFED7" authority="Walker, 1870" authorityName="Walker" authorityYear="1870" box="[151,438,294,320]" class="Insecta" family="Hesperiidae" genus="Pelopidas" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="10" pageNumber="11" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="B976206C7B6ED21FFF6FFEB5FE7FFED7" bold="true" box="[151,438,294,320]" pageId="10" pageNumber="11">
<emphasis id="B976206C7B6ED21FFF6FFEB5FEC5FED7" bold="true" box="[151,268,294,320]" italics="true" pageId="10" pageNumber="11">Pelopidas</emphasis>
<bibRefCitation id="EF93818F7B6ED21FFEEBFEB5FE7FFED7" author="Walker" box="[275,438,294,320]" pageId="10" pageNumber="11" refString="Walker, F. (1870) A list of the butterflies collected by J. K. Lord in Egypt, along the African shore of the Red Sea; and in Arabia; with descriptions of the species new to science. The Entomologist, 5 (4), 48 - 57." type="journal article" year="1870">
Walker, 
<number id="3DCAEE597B6ED21FFE84FEB5FE7FFED7" box="[380,438,294,320]" pageId="10" pageNumber="11" value="1870.0">1870</number>
</bibRefCitation>
</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
</heading>
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="8BBDFC7E7B6ED21FFF6FFEDAFF20FD31" blockId="10.[151,1436,294,678]" pageId="10" pageNumber="11">
<bibRefCitation id="EF93818F7B6ED21FFF6FFEDAFEF3FEF6" author="Walker" box="[151,314,329,353]" pageId="10" pageNumber="11" refString="Walker, F. (1870) A list of the butterflies collected by J. K. Lord in Egypt, along the African shore of the Red Sea; and in Arabia; with descriptions of the species new to science. The Entomologist, 5 (4), 48 - 57." type="journal article" year="1870">
Walker (
<number id="3DCAEE597B6ED21FFF0FFEDAFEFBFEF6" box="[247,306,329,353]" pageId="10" pageNumber="11" value="1870.0">1870</number>
)
</bibRefCitation>
introduced this genus (without describing it) for his new species, 
<emphasis id="B976206C7B6ED21FFBDEFED9FB4AFEF6" box="[1062,1155,329,353]" italics="true" pageId="10" pageNumber="11">P. m i d e a</emphasis>
, now considered to be a synonym of 
<emphasis id="B976206C7B6ED21FFEDCFEFDFEB1FE12" box="[292,376,365,389]" italics="true" pageId="10" pageNumber="11">P. t h r a x</emphasis>
(HÃ¼bner) (
<bibRefCitation id="EF93818F7B6ED21FFE02FEFEFD59FE12" author="Evans" box="[506,656,365,389]" pageId="10" pageNumber="11" refString="Evans, W. H. (1937 a) A catalogue of the African Hesperiidae indicating the classification and nomenclature adopted in the British Museum. British Museum (Natural History), London, UK, 212 pp, 30 plates." type="book" year="1937" yearSuffix="a">
Evans 
<number id="3DCAEE597B6ED21FFDBFFEFEFD4AFE12" box="[583,643,365,389]" pageId="10" pageNumber="11" value="1937.0">1937</number>
a
</bibRefCitation>
). In his revision of the African 
<taxonomicName id="4C0287FD7B6ED21FFC04FEFEFAFDFE12" authority="Evans" authorityName="Evans" authorityYear="1937" box="[1020,1332,365,389]" class="Insecta" family="Hesperiidae" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="10" pageNumber="11" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="family">
Hesperiidae, 
<bibRefCitation id="EF93818F7B6ED21FFB69FEFDFAFDFE12" author="Evans" box="[1169,1332,365,389]" pageId="10" pageNumber="11" refString="Evans, W. H. (1937 a) A catalogue of the African Hesperiidae indicating the classification and nomenclature adopted in the British Museum. British Museum (Natural History), London, UK, 212 pp, 30 plates." type="book" year="1937" yearSuffix="a">
Evans (
<number id="3DCAEE597B6ED21FFB1DFEFEFAD6FE12" box="[1253,1311,365,389]" pageId="10" pageNumber="11" value="1937.0">1937</number>
a)
</bibRefCitation>
</taxonomicName>
included 
<number id="3DCAEE597B6ED21FFF6FFE02FF7AFE3E" box="[151,179,401,425]" pageId="10" pageNumber="11" value="16.0">16</number>
species in 
<taxonomicName id="4C0287FD7B6ED21FFEC8FE02FE69FE3E" box="[304,416,401,425]" class="Insecta" family="Hesperiidae" genus="Pelopidas" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="10" pageNumber="11" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="B976206C7B6ED21FFEC8FE02FE69FE3E" box="[304,416,401,425]" italics="true" pageId="10" pageNumber="11">Pelopidas</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, but when he revised the Eurasian and Australian 
<taxonomicName id="4C0287FD7B6ED21FFC2FFE02FB32FE3E" authority="Evans 1949" authorityName="Evans" authorityYear="1949" box="[983,1275,401,425]" class="Insecta" family="Hesperiidae" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="10" pageNumber="11" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="family">
Hesperiidae (
<bibRefCitation id="EF93818F7B6ED21FFB94FE02FB3AFE3E" author="Evans" box="[1132,1267,401,425]" pageId="10" pageNumber="11" refString="Evans, W. H. (1949) A catalogue of the Hesperiidae from Europe, Asia and Australia in the British Museum (Natural History). British Museum (Natural History), London, 502 pp, 53 plates." type="book" year="1949">
Evans 
<number id="3DCAEE597B6ED21FFB42FE02FB3AFE3E" box="[1210,1267,401,425]" pageId="10" pageNumber="11" value="1949.0">1949</number>
</bibRefCitation>
)
</taxonomicName>
he introduced a new genus, 
<taxonomicName id="4C0287FD7B6ED21FFECFFE26FEB4FE5A" box="[311,381,437,461]" class="Insecta" family="Hesperiidae" genus="Borbo" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="10" pageNumber="11" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="B976206C7B6ED21FFECFFE26FEB4FE5A" box="[311,381,437,461]" italics="true" pageId="10" pageNumber="11">Borbo</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, for most of these, together with three Asian species. 
<taxonomicName id="4C0287FD7B6ED21FFC02FE26FBA3FE5A" box="[1018,1130,437,461]" class="Insecta" family="Hesperiidae" genus="Pelopidas" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="10" pageNumber="11" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="B976206C7B6ED21FFC02FE26FBA3FE5A" box="[1018,1130,437,461]" italics="true" pageId="10" pageNumber="11">Pelopidas</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
was thus restricted to two species found in Africa and Asia, 
<taxonomicName id="4C0287FD7B6ED21FFDEFFE49FD44FE66" authority="Moore, 1881" authorityName="Moore" authorityYear="1881" box="[535,653,473,497]" class="Insecta" family="Hesperiidae" genus="Chapra" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="10" pageNumber="11" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="mathias">
<emphasis id="B976206C7B6ED21FFDEFFE49FD44FE66" box="[535,653,473,497]" italics="true" pageId="10" pageNumber="11">P. mathias</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
and 
<emphasis id="B976206C7B6ED21FFD3CFE49FCD1FE66" box="[708,792,473,497]" italics="true" pageId="10" pageNumber="11">P. t h r a x</emphasis>
, and seven other Asian species. 
<bibRefCitation id="EF93818F7B6ED21FFB6CFE49FAE2FE66" author="Evans" box="[1172,1323,473,497]" pageId="10" pageNumber="11" refString="Evans, W. H. (1949) A catalogue of the Hesperiidae from Europe, Asia and Australia in the British Museum (Natural History). British Museum (Natural History), London, 502 pp, 53 plates." type="book" year="1949">
Evans (
<number id="3DCAEE597B6ED21FFB10FE4AFAEAFE66" box="[1256,1315,473,497]" pageId="10" pageNumber="11" value="1949.0">1949</number>
)
</bibRefCitation>
separated the two genera on the basis that 
<taxonomicName id="4C0287FD7B6ED21FFE04FE6EFDA5FD82" box="[508,620,509,533]" class="Insecta" family="Hesperiidae" genus="Pelopidas" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="10" pageNumber="11" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="B976206C7B6ED21FFE04FE6EFDA5FD82" box="[508,620,509,533]" italics="true" pageId="10" pageNumber="11">Pelopidas</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
has a cell spot on the hind wing underside while 
<taxonomicName id="4C0287FD7B6ED21FFB68FE6EFB1FFD82" box="[1168,1238,509,533]" class="Insecta" family="Hesperiidae" genus="Borbo" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="10" pageNumber="11" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="B976206C7B6ED21FFB68FE6EFB1FFD82" box="[1168,1238,509,533]" italics="true" pageId="10" pageNumber="11">Borbo</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
does not, the mid tibia of 
<taxonomicName id="4C0287FD7B6ED21FFF00FDB2FEA1FDAE" box="[248,360,545,569]" class="Insecta" family="Hesperiidae" genus="Pelopidas" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="10" pageNumber="11" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="B976206C7B6ED21FFF00FDB2FEA1FDAE" box="[248,360,545,569]" italics="true" pageId="10" pageNumber="11">Pelopidas</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
are heavily spined whereas those of 
<taxonomicName id="4C0287FD7B6ED21FFCDFFDB2FCA4FDAE" box="[807,877,545,569]" class="Insecta" family="Hesperiidae" genus="Borbo" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="10" pageNumber="11" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="B976206C7B6ED21FFCDFFDB2FCA4FDAE" box="[807,877,545,569]" italics="true" pageId="10" pageNumber="11">Borbo</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
are unspined (Asian species and some African species) or weakly spined (some African species), and males of 
<taxonomicName id="4C0287FD7B6ED21FFC81FDD6FC20FDCA" box="[889,1001,581,605]" class="Insecta" family="Hesperiidae" genus="Pelopidas" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="10" pageNumber="11" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="B976206C7B6ED21FFC81FDD6FC20FDCA" box="[889,1001,581,605]" italics="true" pageId="10" pageNumber="11">Pelopidas</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
generally have a discal stigma on the forewing upper surface, not seen in 
<taxonomicName id="4C0287FD7B6ED21FFDC6FDFAFD4DFD16" box="[574,644,617,641]" class="Insecta" family="Hesperiidae" genus="Borbo" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="10" pageNumber="11" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="B976206C7B6ED21FFDC6FDFAFD4DFD16" box="[574,644,617,641]" italics="true" pageId="10" pageNumber="11">Borbo</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
. The latter character holds good for all African species of the two genera.
</paragraph>
